{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}} {{Use British English|date=August 2015}} [[File:HomeHousestaircaseatSoane.jpg|thumb|Home House, design by [[Robert Adam]] for the main staircase]] [[File:20-21 Portman Square.jpg|thumb]] '''Home House''' is a [[Georgian_architecture|Georgian]] [[Townhouse (Great Britain)|town house]] at 20 [[Portman Square]], London.<ref name='EngHet'>{{National Heritage List for England |num=1227105 |desc=Home House (Courtauld Institute) |access-date=9 July 2015}}</ref> [[James Wyatt]] was appointed to design it by [[Elizabeth, Countess of Home]] in 1776, but by 1777 he had been dismissed and replaced by [[Robert Adam]]. Elizabeth left the completed house on her death in 1784 to her nephew William Gale, who in turn left it to one of his aunts, Mrs Walsh, in 1785. Its later occupants included the [[Anne-César, Chevalier de la Luzerne|Marquis de la Luzerne]] during his time as French ambassador to the [[Court of St. James's]] (1788 to 1791), the [[John Murray, 4th Duke of Atholl|4th Duke of Atholl]] (1798 to 1808), [[Henry Pelham-Clinton, 4th Duke of Newcastle-under-Lyne|the Duke of Newcastle]] (1820 to 1861), Sir [[Francis Henry Goldsmid]] (1862 to 1919), and [[John Dickson-Poynder, 1st Baron Islington|Lord and Lady Islington]] (1919 to 1926).
In 1926, it was leased by [[Samuel Courtauld (art collector)|Samuel Courtauld]] to house his growing art collection. On his wife's death in 1931, he gave the house and the collection to the fledgling [[Courtauld Institute of Art]] (which he had played a major part in founding) as temporary accommodation. A permanent accommodation was not forthcoming, and the Institute remained in the building until 1989, when it moved to its present home of [[Somerset House]]. Home House was appointed a [[Listed building#Categories of listed building|Grade I]] listed building in 1954.<ref name='EngHet'/> Home House then remained vacant for seven years, until it was acquired by Berkeley Adam Ltd.
It is home to artwork by [[Zaha Hadid]] in the form of a Cocktail Bar, this bar contains her signature sweeping lines and located in No. 21.
